@dev
 | The Trust Channel Manager is an interface for Trust Anchors to collaborate and share directed financial communications channels in as close to a friction-free way as possible.
 |
 | Trust Anchors sign up to collaborate on the Trust Channel, assigning rules that must be in place to allow for the interface to function. Verifiability of documentation is a key differentiating factor from other identity solutions.
 |
 | Technically, the Trust Channel contract acts as a service-interface aggregator, relying heavily on bit-field manipulation to associate the DAG (directed acyclic graph) relations of the participating trust anchor efficiently.
 |
 | This process creates bounds on logic, as lookup tables increase linearly.
 |
 | Within this flow, the Trust Channels are initially set up by the administrators of this smart contract and within each Trust Channel is the ability to add "Trust Channel Administrators", who can manage the membership of each Trust Channel.
 |
 | Some notes: Administrators of Trust Channels do not need to be Trust Anchors.
 | Trust Anchors assigned to Trust Channels must be verified Trust Anchors.
 | When Trust Anchors are added to a Trust Channel by the administrators of that Trust Channel, the Trust Anchor's Jurisdiction is added to the mapping of allowed Jurisdictions in the Trust Channel's routing functionality.
 @notice
 As this methodology evolves, Bloom filters could theoretically be utilized to allow a probablistic pathing that might need to have heavier lookups in the future.
